Dysregulation of MAPK signaling was identified in a previous smaller, proteomic study (
 Seyfried et al., 2017) but has not been clearly identified in transcriptomic studies. MAPK signaling is implicated in many pathways dysregulated in dementia, including immune (
 Jones and Kounatidis, 2017; 
 Lee and Kim, 2017; 
 Zhu et al., 2002), oxidative stress (
 Munoz and Ammit, 2010; 
 Shih et al., 2015), and tau hyperphosphorylation (
 Guise et al., 2001; 
 Kim and Choi, 2010; 
 Wang and Liu, 2008). The potential contribution of PEA-15, one of the C3 modules hubs, to AD pathogenesis has not been studied. Thus, in addition to identifying molecular disease processes previously associated with AD, proteomic co-expression analysis can identify less-established mechanisms.
